ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: What is 15 percent of 1,000?
A pill cures 15 percent of people who have a disease. If 1,000 people have the disease, and they all take the pill, how many people will be cured?
A store is offering a 15 percent off sale on all TVs. The most popular TV is priced at $1000. How much money will a customer save on the television during this sale?
The number 10 is what percent of 1,000?
If the chance of getting a disease is 10 in 1,000, what percent of people will get the disease?
If a customer saved $10 on a $1000 chair, what percent would the customer have saved off the original price?
Which of the following percentages is the biggest?
Notes: 1= One percent; 2= Ten percent; 3= Five percent; 999= Don't know; 998= Refused

ElementDescription: Which of the following percentages represents the biggest risk of getting a disease?
Notes: 1= One percent; 2= Ten percent; 3= Five percent; 999= Don't know; 998= Refused

ElementDescription: Which of the following represents the biggest discount in a sale?
Notes: 1= One percent; 2= Ten percent; 3= Five percent; 999= Don't know; 998= Refused

ElementDescription: Did you find these questions very easy, somewhat easy, somewhat difficult, or very difficult?
